'''Jay Robinson''' (born April 14, 1930) is an [[United States|American]] [[actor]] specialising in [[character actor|character roles]]. He was born in [[New York City]].

==Career==
Robinson began his acting career in [[summer stock theatre]] and repertory companies, and eventually made his way to the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] stage, where he appeared in [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare's]] ''[[As You Like It]]'' and ''[[Much Ado About Nothing]]''. His first film role was as the insane [[Caligula|Emperor Caligula]] in ''[[The Robe (film)|The Robe]]'' (1953), which he reprised in ''[[Demetrius and the Gladiators]]'' (1954). {{Citation needed|date=September 2011}}

This was followed by roles in ''[[The Virgin Queen (film)|The Virgin Queen]]'' (1955) starring [[Bette Davis]], ''[[My Man Godfrey]]'' (1957) with [[David Niven]] and [[June Allyson]] and ''[[Everything You Always Wanted to Know About Sex* (*But Were Afraid to Ask)]]'' (1972), the [[Woody Allen]] comedy and ''[[Bram Stoker's Dracula]]''. He was also featured on two [[Folkways Records|Folkways]] albums of Shakespeare: ''Othello: William Shakespeare'' and ''William Shakespeare: King Richard III'', which were both released in 1964. {{Citation needed|date=September 2011}}

Robinson was the host and narrator for the [[Discovery Channel]] special (and later series) ''Beyond Bizarre'', his many television guest spots include ''[[Star Trek: The Original Series]]'' ("[[Elaan of Troyius]]"), the soap opera ''[[Days of our Lives]]'' (Monty, the homeless drunk), ''[[Planet of the Apes (TV series)|Planet of the Apes]]'' and the late 1970s title role in Sid & Marty Krofft's ''[[Dr. Shrinker]]'', prominently featured on ''[[The Krofft Supershow]]''. He also guest-starred as Cassius Thorne in the ''[[Buck Rogers in the 25th Century (TV series)|Buck Rogers in the 25th Century]]'' episode "Planet of the Amazon Women". He appeared in two episodes of the situation comedy ''[[Bewitched]]'' and on an episode of ''[[Tales of the Gold Monkey]]'' as the Governor in "Last Chance Louie".

He appeared in ''Born Again'' the film adaptation of the book of the same title, about Watergate figure, Charles W. Colson. Robinson played Colson's attorney and Dean Jones starred as Colson.

==Personal life==
In 1958, Robinson was arrested on a narcotics violation and served 15 months in prison. Robinson credits letters of encouragement from friend Bette Davis with helping him find the strength to overcome his problem. She helped him get his first film role in 13 years, in 1971's ''Bunny O'Hare''. Robinson married twice: to Pauline Flowers from 1960 until her death in 2002, and to Gloria Casas since 2004.

